# Study Overview

## What This Document Does

<div class="info-box">
This pipeline performs genome-wide association analysis (GWAS) on blackberry
budbreak phenotypes collected over two field seasons, using the `GWASpoly` package
designed for tetraploid populations. The pipeline runs **80 analyses** organized
into 10 blocks that systematically vary the genetic cohort, statistical covariate,
and year to allow cross-validation and discovery of both year-stable and PF-independent
budbreak QTL.
</div>

All Manhattan plot PNGs are generated once (interactively) and displayed here on
render. **Re-rendering does not re-run any GWAS** — plots are loaded from the output
folder. Only run the generation chunks in RStudio/VSCode, not during render.

## Experimental Material

Two seasons of field data on blackberry budbreak were collected from a diverse
panel of tetraploid genotypes representing breeding lines and commercial varieties.
Plants are of two major types based on the primocane-fruiting (PF) major locus:

| Type | Code | Description |
|------|------|-------------|
| **Floricane-fruiting** | FF | Standard fruiting habit; carries no PF allele |
| **Primocane-fruiting** | PF | Carries dominant PF allele; fruits on first-year canes |
| **Combined panel** | FFPF | All genotypes together |

<div class="warn-box">
**Why PF status matters for GWAS.** The PF locus is strongly associated with
budbreak phenotypes — PF genotypes tend to break bud earlier and more extensively.
If this locus is not accounted for, it will dominate the GWAS signal and mask
genuine chilling-requirement QTL. We address this two ways: (1) **statistically**,
by including PF status as a fixed covariate in the model (Blocks A/E/I), and
(2) **by cohort restriction**, by running GWAS within each type separately so the
PF locus has no variance to generate signal (Blocks B/C/F/G/J).
</div>

## Assessment Dates & Phenotypes

Each year, the same plants were assessed at two timepoints representing increasing
chilling hour accumulation:

| Label | Year 1 Date | Year 2 Date | Approx. Chill Hours |
|-------|-------------|-------------|---------------------|
| **T1** (early) | Dec-27-2024 | Jan-1-2026 | Lower accumulation |
| **T2** (late) | Jan-8-2025 | Jan-30-2026 | Higher accumulation |

Three raw phenotypes were recorded at each timepoint:

| Column | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| Total Buds | Number of buds assessed on each cane |
| Buds Broken | Count of buds showing visible budbreak |
| Derived | Fraction = Broken/Total; Percent = 100×Fraction |

## Why No BLUPs?

<div class="warn-box">
**Double shrinkage problem.** BLUPs (Best Linear Unbiased Predictions) estimate
genotype effects as *random* — they shrink each genotype's estimate toward the
population mean. GWASpoly's kinship matrix correction *also* shrinks associations
toward zero based on genetic relatedness. Stacking these two shrinkage steps can
suppress genuine QTL signal, particularly for rare alleles and smaller-effect loci.
BLUEs (Best Linear Unbiased Estimates) treat genotype as *fixed* — no shrinkage —
and are the appropriate phenotype to pass to a mixed-model GWAS engine like GWASpoly
that handles population structure internally.
</div>

## How Multi-Year GWAS Works Here

GWASpoly was designed for a single phenotype vector per genotype. It has no native
multi-year support. We handle this by **pre-adjusting for year in the phenotype step**:

```
PERCENT ~ Year + Block + Timepoint + NAME
```

The coefficient on each `NAME` level is the **year-adjusted BLUE** — a genotypic
estimate that has been corrected for the systematic mean difference between seasons
before any genomic analysis. This single corrected value is then passed to GWASpoly
as the phenotype for combined-year runs (Blocks I/J).

